f powerful states. Yet older mapping practices persisted: Enlightenment cartography encompassed a wide variety of processes for making, circulating, and using maps of different types. The volume’s more than four hundred encyclopedic articles explore the era’s mapping, covering topics both detailed—such as geodetic surveying, thematic mapping, and map collecting—and broad, such as women and cartography, cartography and the economy, and the art and design of maps. Copious bibliographical references and nearly one thousand full-color illustrations complement the detailed entries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCartographyzEuropey18th centuryxHistoryvEncyclopedias. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aEdney, Matthew H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdney, Matthew H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPedley, Mary Sponberg, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSponberg Pedley, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStauber, Mi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226339221423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226339221.jpg  a978-3-11-069309-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles